        <h1>
          Before you go
        </h1>
        <p>
          Before setting off, there are a few important things to do to make sure your trip is as comfortable,
          fun, and safe as possible. See below a few of our top tips for getting the most out of it.
        </p>
      </section>
      <article>
        <h2>
          Let someone know your plans
        </h2>
        <img src="/images/callsomeone.png" class="large-centre-img">
        <p>
          <b>Call someone</b> and tell them your plans and how long you plan to take. 
          When at camp, you can also send your coordinates with <a href="https://what3words.com">what3words.com</a>
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <h2>
          Complete a checklist
        </h2>
        <img src="/images/checklist.png" class="large-centre-img">
        <p>
         Create a <b>checklist</b> of everything you need, and double check it.
       </p>
     </article>
     <article>
      <h2>
        Identify exit points
      </h2>
      <img src="/images/escape.png" class="large-centre-img">
      <p>
        Before you set off, look at exit points where you can <b>leave the route</b> if you get too tired. 
        You can mark these on a trail app such as <a href="https://hiiker.app">hiiker</a>
      </p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h2>
        Test your equipment
      </h2>
      <img src="/images/compass.png" class="large-centre-img">
      <p>
        Only bring tools you know how to use. <b>test everything in advance</b>, including pitching your shelter.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h2>
        Identify your water sources
      </h2>
      <img src="/images/water.png" class="large-centre-img">
      <p>
        Related to the above, make sure you have done your research on <b>water filling points</b> along your route. 
        Bring plenty to sustain you if water filling opportunities are infrequent.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h2>
        Check your cooking gas
      </h2>
      <img src="/images/gas.png" class="large-centre-img">
      <p>
        Check how much gas is left in your canister to cook with! If you know the empty canister weight, 
        you can weigh the canister with gas to know a rough amount of gas remaining for your trip. 
      </p>
    </article>
